[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating optional dependencies**\n\nI'm considering the public API that includes OAuth2WebClient, which requires an optional dependency of io.vertx:vertx-auth-oauth2. This isn’t included in the test runtime classpath due to being marked optional in the POM. If generated tests try to compile using OAuth2WebClient, it could fail unless I add this dependency. \n\nI’m wondering if meaningful coverage requires it. While it's not strictly necessary for core WebClient coverage, using OAuth2WebClient could be important for complete API coverage.\n\n**Assessing dependency needs**\n\nOkay, I need to evaluate whether the setup for OAuth2 is essential before meaningful coverage can be reached. The existing tests already have meaningful coverage without needing OAuth2. The native run failure seems related to this existing coverage, so special care is needed in setup choices for pre-generation. \n\nIt might be wise to advise ensuring native test runtime args are appropriately set for the new version. I’m considering if optional OAuth2 dependencies are necessary, mainly if testing OAuth2WebClient. If not, the core functionality can still work without it.\n\n**Considering optional dependencies**\n\nI’m looking at the library’s dependency POM, which marks some dependencies as optional. OAuth2WebClient is part of the public API, and documentation likely refers to OAuth2 usage. But I’m not sure if additional setup is needed beyond the normal test scaffold to achieve meaningful coverage.\n\nFor WebClient usage, I see it requires a local HTTP server without needing Docker or external services. I’m pondering whether to include OAuth2 as a deterministic dependency or if it can just be an extra Maven dependency.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0430755c0b6df31c016a403a59f3b881909ed2d7b7699bb66e\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqQDpkukQtnHD